Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Poverty is most frequently conceptualized in terms of material scarcity.
 However, a small number of scholars have suggested over the centuries that
 the lives of the poor may be characterized not only by material deprivation,
 but also negative psychological outcomes.
 In the 
\emph on
Theory of Moral Sentiments
\emph default
, Adam Smith 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{smith_theory_2010}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 cast poverty in terms of its psychological consequences: “[t]he reason
 poverty causes pain is not just because it can leave people feeling hungry,
 cold and sick, but because it is associated with unfavourable regard.
 … The poor man … is ashamed of his poverty.” In his prominent ethnography
 
\emph on
Five Families: Mexian Case Studies in the Culture of Poverty
\emph default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{lewis_five_1959}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, anthropologist Oscar Lewis argued that the lives of the poor were characterize
d by “a strong feeling of marginality, of helplessness, of dependency, of
 not belonging … of inferiority, of personal unworthiness.” A few years later,
 the controversial 
\emph on
Moynihan Report
\emph default
 claimed that poor families in the United States were caught in a “tangle
 of pathology” 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{moynihan_employment_1965}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These suggestions are easy to misunderstand as blaming the poor for their
 poverty by attributing to them certain psychological “shortcomings” which
 keep them mired in poverty.
 Possibly for this reason, the relationship between poverty and psychological
 outcomes has only recently limited attention in the literature.
 However, in 1970s, the question that follows from the assertions cited
 above was posed in earnest: is it true empirically that poverty has psychologic
al correlates? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the resulting literature has concerned itself with the empirical
 relationship between income and self-reported happiness.
 Are poor people unhappier than richer people? In a series of papers, Richard
 Easterlin found that happiness and income were correlated within countries,
 but not across countries; in addition, increases in national income over
 time did not translate into increases in average self-reported happiness.
 Within countries, however, the poor consistently reported lower levels
 of happiness than the rich 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{easterlin_does_1974,easterlin_will_1995,easterlin_income_2001,easterli
n_explaining_2003,easterlin_happiness_2009}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More recently, however, Easterlin’s cross-country finding has been overturned
 by an analysis of a large number of datasets from a broad panel of countries
 by Stevenson, Wolfers, and Sacks 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{stevenson_economic_2008,sacks_subjective_2010,sacks_new_2012}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These authors find a robust relationship between self-reported happiness
 and life satisfaction, both within and across countries.
 
\lang english
Similarly, Kahneman and Deaton 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{kahneman_high_2010}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 show that in the US, higher levels of income and education are correlated
 with life satisfaction.

\lang american
 In addition, happiness has also been associated with income inequality;
 Oishi et al.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{oishi_income_2011}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 find that years with lower levels of income inequality in the US are associated
 with higher levels of self-reported happiness.
 Thus, it appears that poverty and inequality are correlated with self-reported
 happiness and life satisfaction.
 However, it remains unclear whether poverty and inequality affect psychological
 outcomes beyond self-reported happiness and life satisfaction.
 In this paper, we use World Value Survey data from 114,378 respondents
 in 43 countries and show that both within and across countries, low incomes
 are correlated with low intrinsic motivation and trust, less prosocial
 attitudes, and more feelings of meaninglessness.
 Income inequality across countries correlates with loneliness, short-sightednes
s, risk-taking, and low trust.
 These results suggest that poverty and income inequality have broad psychologic
al consequences.
 
\end_layout

