\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this paper was to ask whether poverty has particular psychologica
l consequences.
 A long-standing literature has investigated the association between income
 and happiness; the most recent contributions to this literature document
 an assocation between income and happiness that obtains both within countries,
 as well as across countries.
 Our findings add to this literature in three ways: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we extend previous findings to other psychological outcome variables.
 For decades, the literature on income and psychological outcomes has mainly
 been concerned with happiness and life satisfaction; however, data for
 a host of other important psychological outcome variables is available,
 and our results show that these variables, too, show strong associations
 with income.
 In demonstrating the associations described above, our study lends support
 to a small number of studies that have shown similar associations for optimism,
 locus of control, and self-esteem 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{maqsud_relationships_1991,sherman_interrelationships_1978,twenge_self-
esteem_2002,scheier_optimism_1985,robb_socioeconomic_2009,lynch_understanding_19
97,taylor_psychosocial_1999}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 However, note that these findings were largely obtained in much smaller
 samples, often in particular population subgroups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, our findings lend support to the most recent results by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{stevenson_economic_2008}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which show that the correlation between income and happiness also holds
 across countries, in contrast to the early findings by Easterlin 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{easterlin_does_1974}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In particular, we find that for all variables under consideration, there
 is both a within-country correlation with income category, and a cross-country
 correlation with country GDP.
 In contrast, however, we find no association between any of our psychological
 outcome variables and GDP growth; thus, as countries get richer, they do
 not appear to cahnge much in the psychological variables we consider here.
 A potential explanation for this somewhat surprising result is that yearly
 GDP growth, which we used here as the growth variable, may be too volatile
 and short-term to be reflected in psychological outcomes; a variable that
 aggregates growth over a longer time horizon may show more of an association
 with psychological outcomes in future work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, our findings show that inequality is associated with psychological
 outcomes.
 Previous studies have focused largely on the relationship between psychological
 outcomes and income variables.
 In one study using inequality as a predictor variable, Oishi et al.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
shortcite{oishi_income_2011}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 find that years with lower levels of income inequality in the US are associated
 with higher levels of self-reported happiness.
 We complement this finding by showing that a similar relationship holds
 
\emph on
across
\emph default
 countries: more unequal countries have different psychological outcomes
 than more equal countries, 
\emph on
viz.
 
\emph default
lower trust, more feelings of loneliness and meaninglessness, an inceased
 willingness to help one's family, and more short-sightedness and risk-taking.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In sum, I show a robust effect of income and inequality on a variety of
 psychological outcomes.
 This relationship is robust to a number of control variables.
 It holds both within and across countries, and obtains in the cross-country
 specifications for GDP levels, but not GDP growth.
 Together, these findings suggest that poverty may have significant psychologica
l costs that go beyond economic welfare.
 One might argue that these costs should be on the radar of policymakers,
 since they imply that poverty alleviation programs, to the extent that
 they affect these measures of psychological welfare, have to be evaluated
 not only in terms of their economic effects, but also on their contributions
 to psychological well-being.
 
\end_layout

