\begin_layout Standard
Within-country income data was obtained from the
\emph on
 World Value Survey
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
European Value Survey
\emph default
 data.
 Specifically, the questionnaires for all countries countained a variable
 asking respondents about their household income.
 This variable was coded on a scale from 1-10, corresponding to income deciles
 for the country of residence.
 Thus, 1 means than the respondent was in the lowest 10% of income earners
 in their country of residence; 10 indicates that they were in the top 10%.
 We first z-score this variable and then use it as the main independent
 variable in the within-country regressions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GDP and GDP growth data were taken from the 
\emph on
World Development Indicators
\emph default
 published by the World Bank.
 The data cover the years 1960-2010.
 GDP is measured per capita at purchasing power parity in constant 2005
 US dollars.
 As is common practice, we use the natural logarithm of GDP.
 Growth is measured in % of real GDP.
 These variables are the main independent variables in the cross-country
 regressions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inequality was measured using the Gini coefficients provided by the University
 of Texas Inequality Project (http://utip.gov.utexas.edu/data.html).
 The Gini coefficient is a measure of inequality based on the Lorenz curve,
 which plots cumulative income in a population against the cumulative share
 of people in the population, ordered from lowest to highest shares of income.
 The Gini coefficient is computed from this curve as the ratio of the area
 between the Lorenz curve and the 45 degree line to the area between the
 45 degree line and the x-axis.
 Mathematically, for a cumulative distribution function 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, the Gini coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\frac{1}{\mu}\int_{0}^{\infty}F\left(y\right)\left(1-F\left(y\right)\right)dy
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, the Gini coefficient is zero for perfect equality, i.e.
 all members of a population have the same income, and one for perfect inequalit
y, i.e.
 one member of the population has all the income.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Econometric approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Within countries 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our first question is whether 
\emph on
within
\emph default
 countries, poorer respondents show different psychological outcomes compared
 to richer respondents.
 To answer this question, we regress each variable of interest on the within-cou
ntry income categories for each respondent household.
 Specifically, we fit the following OLS model for each variable of interest:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Psych_{ict}=\alpha_{ct}+\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}Inc_{ict}+\mathbf{\gamma_{ict}}\mathbf{X}_{\mathbf{ict}}+\varepsilon_{ict}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Psych_{ict}$
\end_inset

 is the household-, country-, and year-specific response on the psychological
 variable of interest, 
\begin_inset Formula $Inc_{ict}$
\end_inset

 is the household's income category on a scale from 1 (low) to 10 (high),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ct}$
\end_inset

 captures country and year fixed effects, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{ict}$
\end_inset

 is the error term.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{\mathbf{ict}}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of within-country controls, as described above.
 I run this specification both with and without the inclusion of this vector
 of controls.
 Obervations are weighted with the survey weights provided in the 
\emph on
World Values Survey
\emph default
 dataset, and tandard errors are clustered at the country-year level and
 adjusted for heteroskedasticity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Across countries 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess whether respondents in poorer countries have different psychological
 outcomes on average than those in richer countries, we estimate the following
 models: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Psych_{ict}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\ln y_{ct}+\mathbf{\gamma_{ict}}\mathbf{X}_{\mathbf{ict}}+\mathbf{\delta_{ct}}\mathbf{\Gamma}_{\mathbf{ct}}+\varepsilon_{ict}\label{eq:}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Psych_{ict}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}G_{ct}+\mathbf{\gamma_{ict}}\mathbf{X}_{\mathbf{ict}}+\mathbf{\delta_{ct}}\mathbf{\Gamma}_{\mathbf{ct}}+\varepsilon_{ict}\label{eq:-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Psych_{ict}=\beta_{0}+\beta_{1}\left(\frac{y_{c,t}-y_{c,t-1}}{y_{c,t-1}}\right)+\mathbf{\gamma_{ict}}\mathbf{X}_{\mathbf{ict}}+\mathbf{\delta_{ct}}\mathbf{\Gamma}_{\mathbf{ct}}+\varepsilon_{ict}\label{eq:-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{ct}$
\end_inset

 is the GDP of country 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Gamma_{ct}}$
\end_inset

 is the set of country-level controls described above.
 The three specifications thus test, respectively, the relationship between
 psychological outcomes and the log of GDP (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:"

\end_inset

), GDP growth (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-1"

\end_inset

), and the Gini coefficient (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:-2"

\end_inset

).
 Again these equations are estimated both with and without the set sof controls,
 and standard errors are adjusted for heteroskedasticity and clustered at
 the country-year level.
 Observations are weighted with the inverse frequency of observations per
 country, such that each country is weighted equally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Joint significance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regressions of the psychological outcomes on income, growth, and inequality
 constitute a system of seemingly unrelated regression equations (SUR) that
 can be efficiently estimated with feasible generalized least squares (FGLS).
 This approach allows us to assess whether each of the independent variables
 of interest (income, log GDP, GDP growth, and Gini coefficient) has an
 effect on the psychological outcome variables that is jointly significant
 for the group of outcome variables.
 We report the test statistics for the SUR estimation in the last column
 of the results tables.
\end_layout

